    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "The Word 'Number'",
          "arabic": "كلمة 'رقم'"
        },
        "text": "The fundamental word for 'number' in Egyptian Arabic is 'رقم'. It's a masculine noun.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "رقم",
            "english": "number",
            "transliteration": "raqam"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking 'How many/much?'",
          "arabic": "كيف تسأل 'كم؟'"
        },
        "text": "To inquire about quantity or a number, you use the question word 'كام؟' (kām?). It translates to 'how many?' or 'how much?'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "كام؟",
            "english": "How many/much?",
            "transliteration": "kām?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking 'What is the number?'",
          "arabic": "كيف تسأل 'ما هو الرقم؟'"
        },
        "text": "To ask 'What is the number?' you can say 'الرقم كام؟' (ir-raqam kām?) or simply 'رقم كام؟' (raqam kām?). The 'ال' (il) is the definite article 'the'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "الرقم كام؟",
            "english": "What is the number?",
            "transliteration": "ir-raqam kām?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "رقم كام؟",
            "english": "What number?",
            "transliteration": "raqam kām?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
